    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="609"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d609">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 600.579/8</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-24">
                        <hi rend="italic">November 24, 1914</hi>.</date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 7</hi>.] </dateline>
                <p rend="flushleft">No. 594]</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inform the Department that I
                    have received from His Majesty’s Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs copies
                    of lists of articles, the exportation of which the kingdoms of <pb facs="0715"
                        n="401" xml:id="pg_401"/> Norway, Sweden, and Denmark have prohibited under
                    agreement with the British Government, and I beg to enclose herewith these
                    copies in duplicate.<note n="1" xml:id="d609fn1">Not printed; of considerable
                        length. They resemble in general the Dutch list summarized ante, <ref
                            target="#pg_388">p. 388</ref>. See also the Ambassador’s telegrams Nos.
                        1202, December 6, and 1209, December 7, regarding the inclusion of copper in
                        the Swedish list, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_356">pp.
                            356</ref>, <ref target="#pg_359">359</ref>.</note> In this connection I
                    further have the honor to inform the Department of the fact that these lists
                    form an integral part of the program as to contraband which has been adopted, by
                    His Majesty’s Government.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Walter Nines Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
